title: Baluk Willam Nature Conservation Reserve, Belgrave
description:
Baluk Willam Reserve is a small park in Belgrave South and has a significant number of orchids and other flora.  

The plant list used is based on the flora list on the Friends of Baluk Willam - 
http://home.vicnet.net.au/~fobw/

The Orchid Species List contains all orchids recorded in the reserve historically. The Flora Species List contains vascular plants, including only some orchids at this stage.

items.title: Cryptostylis leptochila
items.content_text:
Only two individuals were found still in flowers at this time.
Lots of leaves and several withered flower stems were sighted.

items.title: Pterostylis grandiflora
items.content_text: Probably the first individual with fully opened flower in the reserve.

items.title: Pterostylis grandiflora
items.content_text: A small plant about 10 cm high with lance-shaped leaves. The flowers were attractive with the central sepal (green) and lateral petals (brown) fused to form a hood, rising up and over the labellum. The lateral sepals were fused at the base and rose up on either side to erect points. The inside of the hood showed broad white stripes (pic 5). The same colouring could be seen on the outer side of the flower (pic 3).

items.title: Poranthera microphylla s.s.
items.content_text: Herbaceous plant about 5 cm tall with erect stems bearing clusters of small white flowers. Leaves were elongated egg-shaped, some small and some large. The plant had bright green loculated fruit.

items.title: Thelymitra ixioides s.l.
items.content_text:
Tall plant with beautiful blue flowers with purplish tinge ot the outer surface of sepals. Yellow pollinia was visible at the tip of the column. Stigmatic surface showed a dense tuft of white hairs. Leaves were erect and narrow ( not seen here).
Spotted in semi-shade in a reserve with eucalypts and natives - dry sclerophyll forest.
The flowers bloom in October and November.

items.title: Microtis arenaria
items.content_text:
Called the "Notched Onion-orchid" this orchid plant was about 50 cm high. I could see a single long sheath like leaf from the centre of which rose a slender green stem bearing a spike of flowers. 
The central sepal was hooded covering the petals. Lateral sepals curled backwards. The lip was bilobed with a slightly wavy margin.
At first this plant looked like it had unopened buds- the flowers were so small and are not conspicuous. They are apparently scented ! 
Spotted in semi-shade.

items.title: Pimelea flava subsp. flava
items.content_text:
A very leggy open shrub with leaves layered along the stems and clusters of small yellow flowers at the outer ends. Shrub was about 1.4 metres tall, same wide, each flower was about 12mm across.
In a dry sclerophyll forest dominated by silver leafed stringybark eucalyptus. Baluk William Flora Reserve.

items.title: Goodenia lanata
items.content_text:
Flower about 35mm across and about 20cm above the ground. The stem had very few leaves (3) and meandered prostrate through grasses for about 30cm before rising. Only two of these plants were found in about 3 acres of bush.
In a dry sclerophyll forest dominated by silver leafed stringybark eucalyptus. Baluk William Flora Reserve.
Also called 'Native Promrose'

items.title: Coronidium scorpioides s.s.
items.content_text:
An asteraceae which looks frayed around the margin when fresh. Flowers about 40cm above ground on smokey green stem. About 35mm wide.
In a dry sclerophyll forest dominated by silver leafed stringybark eucalyptus. Baluk William Flora Reserve.
Also called Helichrysum scorpioides

items.title: Diplarrena moraea
items.content_text:
This plant was the only one of it's type in a large, mixed native, bushland so it really stood out. About 80cm tall with 4 or 5 flower stems coming from a dense clump of dark green, long, blade-like leaves.
In a dry sclerophyll forest dominated by silver leafed stringybark eucalyptus. Baluk William Flora Reserve.
Very much Victoria and Tasmania.

items.title: Caladenia carnea s.s., Leistomorpha brontoscopa
items.content_text:
About 30cm tall on a fine wiry stem. Pinkish white flower about 20mm across. Moth about 10mm long.
In a dry sclerophyll forest dominated by silver leafed stringybark eucalyptus. Baluk William Flora Reserve.
Common names for this flower include all combinations of 'fingers' 'lady' 'striped' and 'pink' (lol) 
Caladenia carnea is very likely to be a complex of related species. 
Atlas of Living Australia has flags on this for 'Extinct' in Victoria !?

items.title: Candalides hyacinthina
items.content_text:
About 35mm wingspan. Several of these frolicking in the grasses of a local orchid reserve. Some were darker and bluer than others. Two specimens here - one was chasing the other.
Understory in dry eucalyptus woodlands. Baluk William Flora Reserve
This name is mis-spelled on ALA as C hyacinthinus instead of C hyacinthina  ??

items.title: Entoloma moongum
items.content_text: About 50mm tall and wearing Halloween black but with classic free white gills and white mycelia around the base of the stipe. Also note slightly marginate gills. Entoloma moongum

items.title: Calochilus paludosus
items.content_text: A dramatic flower about 300mm above ground on a straight stem (slightly thicker than other orchids in the area)

items.title: Thysanotus patersonii
items.content_text: An attractive tiny climbing vine with flowers about 10mm wide but no visible leaves. The wiry stems use anything down to the size of grass stems to wind themselves around.

items.title: Chiloglottis valida
items.content_text: These were low growing from two oval shaped leaves up to about 70mm above the ground and about 40mm wide. Roughly half a dozen calli occur in the rear part of the labellum plus a single taller stalked callus standing in the back. The calli decrease in size to the front. The orchids dupe male Thynnus sp. (flower wasps) by producing the 'scent' of a female wasp. The flower has a large labellum including a group of dark, shiny calli (stemmed knobs and buttons) with a particular 'insectiform' arrangement. The broader callus at the centre is what the male wasp grasps at causing the labellum to collapse upwards. The waspâ€™s thorax is then coated with pollen as it fights it's way out.

items.title: Cryptostylis leptochila
items.content_text: Almost leafless orchids about 50cm tall with a dramatic flower designed to attract a particular type of male wasp - the Orchid Dupe wasp.

items.title: Corybas unguiculatus
items.content_text: Hard to spot amongst the fallen leaves. Reddish-purple flower about 10mm long.

items.title: Banksia marginata
items.content_text: Small loose shrubs of Banksia marginata to 1.5m coming into flower at Balluk Willum Flora Reserve Sth Belgrave.

items.title: Centaurium erythraea
items.content_text: Lots of these flowers throughout the reserve, along the tracks.

items.title: Gompholobium huegelii
items.content_text: Striking yellow flowers

items.title: Wahlenbergia spp.
items.content_text: Particularly deep blue flower on this bluebell - flower stem about 15cm. Leaves in photo were noticably wavy edged about 12mm to 15mm wide.

items.title: Cryptostylis leptochila
items.content_text: Small Tounge Orchid growing beside Orchid Rd. Flower spikes 30-40cm tall.

items.title: Pterostylis atrans
items.content_text: Growing beside the nature trail at the south west end of Baluk Willam Flora and Fauna Reserve Belgrave South. About 20cm tall with 3-4 small leaves wrapped around the stem like the one shown. No basal leaves evident.
